definition: "Reverse T3 (rT3) is an inactive isomer of T3 (triiodothyronine) produced when the prohormone T4 (thyroxine) is deiodinated at the 5-position (inner ring) by type 3 deiodinase (DIO3), rather than at the 5'-position (outer ring) by type 1 or type 2 deiodinase — which would produce the biologically active T3. The result is a structurally similar but functionally inactive molecule: rT3 can bind to thyroid hormone receptors but does not activate them, and in high concentrations may competitively inhibit active T3 binding. Under normal physiological conditions, approximately 20% of T4 conversion is directed toward rT3 production, with 40% going to active T3; the remainder undergoes alternative deiodination pathways. In states of physiological stress, illness, caloric restriction, or elevated cortisol, the ratio shifts dramatically — DIO3 activity increases and DIO1/DIO2 activity decreases, shunting T4 conversion strongly toward rT3. This reduces active T3 availability, applying the metabolic brakes when the body needs to conserve energy."
why_it_matters: "Reverse T3 sits at the intersection of thyroid function, stress physiology, and metabolic efficiency. Its primary clinical significance is as a marker of the physiological adaptation called 'non-thyroidal illness syndrome' (NTIS) or 'euthyroid sick syndrome' — a state in which TSH and free T4 may be normal or only mildly abnormal, but conversion of T4 to active T3 is substantially impaired, with rT3 elevated and free T3 reduced. This pattern is expected and physiologically appropriate in acute severe illness (where conserving metabolic resources matters), but when it persists in the context of chronic conditions — prolonged cortisol elevation, chronic inflammation, severe caloric restriction, or chronic illness — it produces a state of functional hypothyroidism at the tissue level that standard thyroid testing (TSH, FT4) may entirely miss. For longevity medicine practitioners, rT3 is a third dimension of thyroid assessment that completes the Free T3/Free T4 picture, particularly in patients with persistent hypothyroid symptoms despite normal TSH. The FT3:rT3 ratio is a more sensitive marker of tissue thyroid hormone availability than any single measurement alone."

